@node INTRODUCTION "INTRODUCTION..."

Yeah, another update of this famous Viewer reached your BBS...since the last
release in june,1994, many things have changed...some new packers are 
included, some routines were rewritten to give you the maximum speed avail-
able on your machine and of course many bugfixings have been done. To get
an overview what's new/changed in this Public Release of my Viewer, take
a look to the @{b}HISTORY-FILE@{ub} included in this archive.

Another major changing is the fact that mEGA-vIEW and all other programs I
will made in the future are declared as @{b}SHAREWARE@{ub}, which means, that you
have to pay a registration fee to become the newest versions...this Version
of mEGA-vIEW is 100% working version without any restrictions, but I don't
release any update of the viewer in the future, all changings will then
only be accessable for @{"Registered Users" LINK REGISTER}...
@endnode

@node QUICKFEATURES "SHORT OVERVIEW OF THE FEATURES"
@{u}Features are :@{uu}

 - Supports Wildcards (*)

 - @{b}Viewing/Downloading@{ub} Files directly from a @{b}LHA/ZIP-Archive@{ub}

 - Integrated Sysop-View (editable via @{"Tooltypes" LINK TOOLTYPES})

 - Securitycheck for @{"RESTRICTED FILES" LINK RESTRICT}

 - Fileidentification via FileID.Library by BloodRock/Syndicate

 - New option to @{b}view AmigaGuide® - Databases as ANSI-Files@{ub} 

 - @{b}DMS/ARJ/EXE/SHRINK/ZOO/ZOOM/WARP/LZX@{ub}-Checker supported

 - Don't break viewing if a character with ascii-value >128 was found...

 - Supports '@{b}NS@{ub}' to view files NonStop...useful for BBS-Adverts..

 - Could @{b}Extract@{ub} and show @{b}FILE_ID.DIZ@{ub} from @{b}EXEcutables@{ub} or @{b}DMS-Archives@{ub}

 - Extraoption to choose at which Accesslevel a user could view (and test of
   coz :-} ), otherwise he could only test files/archives...

 - @{b}CRSR-Keys@{ub} used to choose a file for viewing/dl'ing from @{b}LHA/ZIP@{ub}-archives

 - @{b}Hexadecimaloutput@{ub} (similar to the DirectoryOpus-Function HEXREAD) for all 
   unknown or not supported Files (i.e. MS-DOS Executables!)

 - Is able to show the Tooltypes of Project- ,Tool- & Drawer-Icons

and many other cewl Functions....if ya now interested, then @{"install" LINK REQUIREMENTS} it 
to your /X-System...
@endnode

@node FEATURES "MAIN FEATURES AND OTHER REASONS TO USE THIS TOOL"
I don't believe that you have any problems, coz mEGA-vIEW works similar
to the original /X viewer, but has some more powerful enhancements, like :

@{u}1.) You could use NS@{uu}

If you want to view a file Nonstop, that means that mEGA-vIEW don't prompt
you to continue,etc., all you have to do is to enter NS after the Filename,
i.e.:
                           @{b}Diabolo.doc NS @{ub}

will show Diabolo.doc nonstop..or if you enter :

                              @{b}Dia* NS@{ub}

lets mEGA-vIEW search for all patterns matching "DIA*" and then show the 
desired file nonstop.
This works anywhere, you could enter @{b}NS@{ub} after the filename and the selected 
file will be shown nonstop.

@{u}2.) Using WildCards@{uu}

This Feature was the main reason why I wrote this Tool ...:) 

You could use wildcards as much as you want it to do so...:) , and in 
difference to AmieX, you DON'T have to enter three real Chars before
using Wildcards, so you could call mEGA-vIEW like:
 
                       @{b}V S:START*@{ub}

...searches for files in S:, which contains the pattern START*...or 
enter something like this :

                       @{b}V S:SH*LL-ST*ART*P NS@{ub}

will search for all patterns which matches the pattern and then show the
desired file NonStop
                       @{b}V S:*@{ub}

...shows you ALL files which are found in Drawer S:...this works also for
the "normal" viewmode (NO SYSOPVIEW), i.e.

                       @{b}V *@{ub}

shows you @{b}ALL@{ub} files which are found in the current DL-Pathes. Nice eh ?! :)

@{u}3.) Testing Archives@{uu}

If you select a archive, you have always the choice to @{b}test@{ub} it. If mEGA-vIEW
recognize an archive, you were asked to view the @{b}contents/informations@{ub}...
enter now @{b}'T'@{ub} and the desired archive will be tested...hope you enjoy the
@{b}realtime testings via PIPE:@{ub} ...:) Don't get confused if you see four different
Testmodes by LHA...LHA V1.50r gives you the option to change the output. I've
included a randommode which changes the LHA-Output at every call...so don't
think this is a mistake or a Virus or whatever...it's only my mad brain..:()

@{u}4.) Filerecognizing@{uu}

Now mEGA-vIEW is able to check which filetype you've selected by using the
@{b}FileID.Library@{ub} from BloodRock/Syndicate. It's no longer possible to confuse
the viewer,i.e. Rename a LHA-Archive in xxxxxxxx.DMS and try to view it with
V1.0...the first Version tries to open it as DMS-archive. In this new Version,
also such renamed files will be identified correctly.

@{u}5.) Restricted Files@{uu}

A main changing was the handling of @{"RESTRICTED FILES" LINK RESTRICT}. In V1.0, I only check 
for Restricted Files defined in ACP. Now mEGA-vIEW checks out the @{"ACP" LINK ACP} Icon and
if not found, it checks now the FileComments for the Keyword '@{b}RESTRICTED@{ub}'. If
found, it breaks and inform the user that this file is restricted. This works
also if you select a file from an archive for viewing/downloading, which is 
marked as restricted.

@{u}6.) CRSR-Keys@{uu}

If you select a @{b}LHA/ZIP-archive@{ub} you will see the contents of this archive and
you could now use the @{b}CRSR up/down keys@{ub} to select the file you want to view or
download.

After finding out that some Terminal-Programs like '@{b}TERMINUS@{ub}' on Amiga or
'@{b}Telemate@{ub}' on PC have some problems to emulate the CRSR-Keys, I have enhanced
the CRSR-Keys to use the keys @{b}8@{ub} & @{b}2@{ub}, too. So if you couldn't use the CRSR-
keys, use @{b}8 for up and 2 for down@{ub} instead.

@{u}NOTE:@{uu} mEGA-vIEW sorts out some filenames which could make problems, i.e. File-
      Names like @{b}'#?#?#'@{ub} , @{b}'*'@{ub} @{b}'SECOM CITY.DISPLAYME'@{ub} and so on.
      I sorted out this files otherwise it is possible that the @{b}whole@{ub} (!) 
      archive will be extracted ! So don't worry if you don't find the right 
      file. 
      If you want to view such files, @{u}DOWNLOAD THE ARCHIVE AND TAKE A LOOK@{uu} 
      @{u}AT HOME !@{uu}

      Don't think I'm lame coz I know that's possible to extract such files, 
      but always remember : It's a TextViewer not a replacement for the Down-
      loadcommand ! 

@{u}7.) Downloading FROM archives@{uu}

This option allows users with the correct Accesslevel to @{b}Download@{ub} a file from
a @{b}LHA@{ub} or @{b}ZIP@{ub}-archive. After selecting the desired File via @{b}CRSR-Keys@{ub}, you were
asked to Download, view normal or view nonstop the file. Of course you could 
forbid the downloading by deactivating the ToolType @{"DL_LEVEL" LINK DLLEVEL}.
If you select @{b}D@{ub} for Download mEGA-vIEW checks your ratio (bytes) and 
if you were able to download something, you will receive the selected File 
via @{b}ZModem@{ub}. If the user has a disabled Ratio no checkings were made.
This Option works similar for @{b}LHA and ZIP-Archives@{ub}.

@{u}8.) Hex-Output@{uu}

If you select a file which couldn't supported (i.e. MS-DOS Executables or
Soundmods) mEGA-vIEW first tries to identify the File and then you were asked
to view this file anyway. If you enter '@{b}Y@{ub}'es you get an @{b}Hexadecimal-Output@{ub}
from the selected File. If you use DirectoryOpus you should know this output,
coz it's exactly the same output like DOpus' HEXREAD. I have included this 
option to avoid a destroyed Screen, coz normally you won't VIEW A SOUNDMODULE 
for example, and if you do so you will see only garbarge on the screen. But 
under Hexoutput you could read all printable characters without Screen-
flashings,Beeps and whatever...of coz the file will be checked for @{"RESTRICTED" LINK RESTRICT} 
before displaying.
It could happen that the FileID.Library don't recognize a file correctly, in
this case you won't see the Hex-Output ! mEGA-vIEW show you the file like a 
Textfile and therefor you will get a destroyed Screen....
@endnode
                                                                                
@node REQUIREMENTS "WHAT YOU NEED TO INSTALL mEGA-vIEW"
@{u}First U need...@{uu}

 - any @{b}Amigamodel@{ub} (A500-A4000T) with @{b}Kickstart 2.04++@{ub}

 - the installed /X-Software (Tested on /X 3.xx/4.xx ..don't know if it
   runs correctly under /X 2.xx...if someone could test it please @{"INFORM" LINK BBSADVERT1}
   me !)

 - @{b}FileID.Library V5++ in LIBS:@{ub}

 - To take advantage of the packersupport I recommend to use the following 
   Tools to get the "full power" of mEGA-vIEW:

   For @{b}LHA@{ub} use @{b}LHA V1.50r@{ub} by Stefan Boberg
   
   For @{b}DMS@{ub} use @{b}DMS V1.03/V1.11/V1.51/V1.53/V2.04@{ub} by ParCon-Software
   
   For @{b}ZIP@{ub} use @{b}UnZip V5.1@{ub} by Info-ZIP (@{u}And only this or higher Version@{uu} , 
                           earlier Versions won't work correct!!!!)

   For @{b}ARJ@{ub} use @{b}UnARJ V1.15/V2.41@{ub} by Robert K Jung

   For @{b}EXE@{ub} use @{b}Executable Hunk Checker V1.0Beta@{ub} by Shagratt/LSD

   For @{b}GUIDE@{ub} use @{b}Guide2DocProf V0.3@{ub} by fOX/rEMEDY^aSPECT

   For @{b}SHRINK@{ub} use @{b}SHRINK V1.1@{ub} by Matthias Meixner

   @{u}Changings to V2.05:@{uu}

   For @{b}ZOO@{ub} use @{b}ZOO V2.1@{ub} written by Unknown...

   For @{b}ZOOM@{ub} use @{b}ZOOMCHK V.01@{ub} by Carnivore/Beermacht

   For @{b}WARP@{ub} use @{b}WARPCK V1.4@{ub} by Mike Thomas and Doug Keller

   For @{b}LZX@{ub} use @{b}LZX V1.00@{ub} by Data Compression Technologies.

   For @{b}FILE_ID.DIZ-Support@{ub} you need @{b}DMSDESCRIPT/EXEDESCRIPT@{ub} by @{b}Remo/MST@{ub} 
  
 - The Device @{b}PIPE:@{ub} already mounted (Used for testing archives...!)

 - Some files to view....:)

To install mEGA-vIEW, copy @{b}'mEGA-vIEW'@{ub} & @{b}'mEGA-vIEW.info'@{ub} to the directory
where you stored your /X-Tools.

@{u}NOTE:@{uu} Make sure that you place the icon in the same directory like the main
      program, otherwise mEGA-vIEW couldn't find it...!

Now copy the icons @{b}'V.INFO'@{ub} and @{b}'VS.INFO'@{ub} to @{b}BBS:COMMANDS/BBSCMD/@{ub}

After this, copy all packers from the included @{b}C-Dir@{ub} to your @{b}C-directory@{ub}.

Copy @{b}FileID.Library@{ub} to @{b}LIBS:@{ub}, and if you want to use the @{b}Locale-Feature@{ub} of the
Library, copy the @{b}FileID.catalog@{ub} to your @{b}LOCALE:CATALOGS/DEUTSCH/@{ub} drawer.

Now before using mEGA-vIEW, please take a look to chapter @{"TOOLTYPES" LINK TOOLTYPES} and check
out the pathes.

@endnode

@node TOOLTYPES "ALL TOOLTYPE-INFORMATIONS FOR mEGA-vIEW V2.05"

                   @{b}All Tooltypes from mEGA-vIEW V2.05 :@{ub}

@{u}1) Definitions for Supported Filetypes@{uu}

   @{"    LHA_PATH    " LINK LHA} - Path for LHA
   @{"    DMS_PATH    " LINK DMS} - Path for DMS
   @{"   DMS_FILEID   " LINK DMSID} - Path for DMSDescript (FileID_DIZ from DMS)
   @{"    ZIP_PATH    " LINK ZIP} - Path for UnZIP       
   @{"    ARJ_PATH    " LINK ARJ} - Path for UnARJ
   @{"   SHRINK_PATH  " LINK SHR} - Path for SHRINK
   @{"    EXE_PATH    " LINK EXE} - Path for CheckExe 
   @{"   EXE_FILEID   " LINK EXEID} - Path for EXEDescript (FileID_DIZ from EXEcutables)
   @{"   GUIDE_PATH   " LINK GUIDE} - Path for Guide2DocProf (converts GUIDE to ANSI)
   @{"    ZOO_PATH    " LINK ZOO} - Path for ZOO
   @{"   ZOOM_PATH    " LINK ZOOM} - Path for ZOOMCHK
   @{"   WARP_PATH    " LINK WARP} - Path for WARPCK
   @{"    LZX_PATH    " LINK LZX} - Path for LZX

@{u}2) Other Definitions@{uu}
                          
   @{"   TEMP_PATH    " LINK TEMP} - Path for Temporary Files
   @{"    ACP_PATH    " LINK ACP} - Path to ACP.INFO        
   @{"   CALLERSLOG   " LINK CALLERSLOG} - Write to CallersLog (YES or NO)
   @{"   ONLY_CHECK   " LINK ONLYCHECK} - Accesslevel for viewing files
   @{"    DL_LEVEL    " LINK DLLEVEL} - Accesslevel for Downloading    
   @{" SYSOPVIEWLEVEL " LINK SYSOPVIEW} - Accesslevel for Sysopview

@endnode
                                                                            
@node LHA "SUPPORT OF LHA/LZH-ARCHIVES"
@{b}                              LHA_PATH=<path>                             
-  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -
@{ub}
Here you specify the complete path to @{b}LHA@{ub}, i.e. LHA_PATH=C:LHA. If this Tool-
type is not set or the path is incorrect, LHA-Support is disabled.

If you set it correct, users have the ability to @{b}view/download *ONE* file@{ub} 
directly from the selected archive. If an user selects a LHA/LZH-archive, he
will be asked first to @{b}View@{ub} or @{b}Test@{ub} the desired archive. 
If the accesslevel defined in @{"ONLY_CHECK" LINK ONLYCHECK} is higher than the user's access-
level, the viewing is disabled and he could only test archives. 
If the user selects (@{b}T@{ub})est, mEGA-vIEW tests the archive via LHA.
Don't get confused if you see four different LHA-Testoutputs, coz I have re-
written the Testroutine to use all Displaymodes available by LHA V1.50r by 
choosing it randomly.

If the user selects Viewing, mEGA-vIEW first loads in the Contentslist of the
desired archive and sorts out filenames with special chars or spaces in it,i.e.
files containing '#?', '*', 'BBS ADVERT.TXT' etc. won't be shown in the list.
So if you don't find your favourite BBS-Advert, DOWNLOAD THE WHOLE ARCHIVE AND
TAKE A LOOK AT HOME! I have to disable this filenames, coz LHA interprets them
as command to extract the @{b}WHOLE(!)@{ub} archive...After sorting out U get a list of
the remaining files inside the archive in alphabetical order. The list will be
shown in two rows.The file which is actually selected will be shown in white, 
all other files are blue. Press now @{b}CRSR-UP/DOWN@{ub} to walk through the list. In
the middle of the list U could see an arrow pointing to the current selected 
file. This is useful if you have @{b}ANSI-COLORS off@{ub} in Amiex, coz without 
colors you won't see which file you have selected, but with this arrow you 
always know which file is selected. 
The @{b}CRSR-Keys LEFT/RIGHT@{ub} are not supported coz you don't need them.
If you scroll over the first/last entry in the list you fly back to the last/ 
first file in the list. When U found the file you want to take a look to, 
press 'ENTER' and the selected file will be extracted from the archive.

It could happen that there are more files inside the archive as could be 
displayed at one time on your screen. In this case you are able to switch to
the next entries by pressing @{b}Space@{ub}. If all entries fit on your screen, the
'@{b}SPACE@{ub}' - Key is disabled. By pressing '@{b}ESC@{ub}' you get back to the Fileprompt
of mEGA-vIEW.

If the user has an accesslevel higher or equal to the accesslevel defined in
the ToolType @{"DL_LEVEL" LINK DLLEVEL}, he could choose between (@{b}D@{ub})ownloading the file, view
Non(@{b}S@{ub})top, (@{b}Q@{ub})uit to Fileprompt or (@{b}ENTER@{ub}) to view normal. If he choose '@{b}D@{ub}' for
Downloading mEGA-vIEW first checks if the user has enough uploads to download
something. If not, mEGA-vIEW stops and writes a message. Otherwise the user's
Up/Downloading-Statistics and the selected file (with Bytesize) will be 
displayed. If he/she has a Disabled Ratio, no checkings were made and a small
comment were printed after the DailyBytes. 
Pressing (@{b}ENTER@{ub}) starts the @{b}ZModem-Transfer@{ub}, (@{b}A@{ub})borts the transfer.
After a successful transfer the Downloadstats from the user where changed and
written to /X. Then mEGA-vIEW jumps back to the fileprompt.

If the user hasn't the correct level to Download, he could only choose between 
normal and Nonstop-View. 
@endnode
                        
@node DMS "SUPPORT OF DMS-ARCHIVES"
@{b}                              DMS_PATH=<path>
-  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -
@{ub}
Here you specify the complete path to @{b}DMS@{ub}, i.e. DMS_PATH=C:DMS. If this Tool-
type is not set or the path is incorrect, DMS-Support is disabled.

If you set it correct, users have the ability to @{b}view informations@{ub} or to @{b}test@{ub}
the desired DMS-archive. If the user wants to test the archive, mEGA-vIEW calls
@{b}DMS@{ub} with the argument 'TEST' and redirect the output to PIPE:. From PIPE: it
will displayed to the user so that it runs in '@{b}RealTime@{ub}'...:)

If the user selects '@{b}View@{ub}', he will see the Standard-Informations from DMS
(mEGA-vIEW calls @{b}DMS@{ub} with the argument @{b}VIEW@{ub} and redirect the output to a file,
which will be displayed). 

If you have set the ToolType @{"DMS_FILEID" LINK DMSID} correct, mEGA-vIEW searches for the
Filedescription inside the DMS-Archive and if found, you were asked to view it.
If you don't set @{b}DMS_FILEID@{ub}, mEGA-vIEW display only the informations
from the archive and get back to the fileprompt.

@{"Thanx" LINK GREETS} must go to @{b}Re/Y\o/MST@{ub} for the Program @{b}DMSDESCRIPT V1.0@{ub}...
@endnode

@node DMSID "SUPPORT OF FILE_ID.DIZ IN DMS-ARCHIVES"
@{b}                            DMS_FILEID=<path>
-  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -
@{ub}
Here you define the complete path to @{b}DMSDescript@{ub} written by @{b}Re/Y\o/MsT@{ub}, i.e.
DMS_FILEID=C:DMSDESCRIPT. If this Tooltype isn't set mEGA-vIEW wouldn't 
search for @{b}FILE_ID.DIZ@{ub} inside a DMS-archive. If you set this ToolType correct,
mEGA-vIEW search for a Filedescription inside the archive after displaying
the informations and if found, it will be displayed to the user.
 
Big @{"Thanx" LINK GREETS} must go to @{b}Remo/MST@{ub} for his @{b}DMSDescript@{ub}.
@endnode

@node ZIP "SUPPORT OF ZIP-ARCHIVES"
@{b}                              ZIP_PATH=<path>
-  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -
@{ub}
Here you specify the complete path to @{b}(Un)ZIP@{ub}, i.e. ZIP_PATH=C:UNZIP. If this
ToolType is not set or the path is incorrect, ZIP-Support is disabled.

If you set it correctly, users have the ability to @{b}view/download@{ub} a file
directly from a @{b}ZIP-Archive@{ub}. The function of this Support is exactly the same
like @{b}LHA-Support@{ub}. If a user has an equal or higher accesslevel as defined in
@{"DL_LEVEL" LINK DLLEVEL}, he could download @{b}*ONE*@{ub} file from the archive, otherwise he could
only view it. For detailed information about the options look in Chapter @{"LHA" LINK LHA},
as this two packers are both uses the same Selection-Routine.

@{u}NOTE:@{uu} Make sure that you only use @{b}UnZIP@{ub} (or ZIP) upto @{b}V5.1@{ub}, coz this is the 
      first Version that allows you to specify an Extractpath for 'Unzipping'.
      The second major enhancement from @{b}UnZIP@{ub} is the option to create a 
      Contents-List like @{b}LHA@{ub} (only Names), and therefor I could handle ZIP
      in the same way...
      If the ZIP-Support won't work check out your Version from UnZip. I've 
      included the correct Version of UnZIP in this package.
      All Versions lower than the one i've included (V5.1) @{u}WON'T WORK WITH@{uu}
      @{u}mEGA-vIEW !!!!@{uu}
@endnode

@node ARJ "SUPPORT OF ARJ-ARCHIVES"
@{b}                              ARJ_PATH=<path>
-  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -
@{ub}
Here you specify the complete path to @{b}ARJ@{ub}, i.e. ARJ_PATH=C:UNARJ. If this Tool-
type is not set or the path is incorrect, ARJ-Support is disabled.

If you set it correct, users have the ability to @{b}view@{ub} the contents or to @{b}test@{ub} 
the desired ARJ-archive. If the user wants to test the archive, mEGA-vIEW calls
@{b}ARJ@{ub} and redirects the Output to PIPE: to show you the testing in '@{b}RealTime@{ub}'.

If the user selects '@{b}VIEW@{ub}' mEGA-vIEW reads in the contents of the ARJ-archive
and display it to the user. 

@{u}NOTE:@{uu} It's impossible to extract only one file with @{b}UnARJ V1.15@{ub}, which I used
      to implement this function. If someone has a newer Version which allows
      extracting of single files, please send it to me and I will rewrite the
      code to make it possible to view single files (maybe with Downloading
      like @{"LHA" LINK LHA} or @{"ZIP" LINK ZIP}). 

To get in Contact with me take a look to chapter @{"ADRESS" LINK BBSADVERT1}...
@endnode

@node SHR "SUPPORT OF SHRINK-ARCHIVES"
@{b}                            SHRINK_PATH=<path>
-  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -
@{ub}
Here you specify the complete path to @{b}SHRINK@{ub}, i.e. SHRINK_PATH=C:SHRINK. If 
this Tooltype is not set or the path is incorrect, SHRINK-Support is disabled.

If you set it correct, users have the ability to @{b}view@{ub} the contents or to @{b}test@{ub}
the desired SHRINK-archive. If the user wants to test the archive, mEGA-vIEW 
calls @{b}SHRINK@{ub} and redirects the Output to PIPE: to show you the testing 
in 'RealTime'...:)

If the user selects '@{b}VIEW@{ub}' mEGA-vIEW displays the contents of the selected
SHRINK-archive via PIPE: .

@{u}NOTE:@{uu} Like @{"UnARJ" LINK ARJ} it's impossible to extract only one file with @{b}SHRINK V1.1@{ub}, 
      which I used to implement this function. If someone has a newer Version 
      with extracting of single files, please send it to me and I will rewrite 
      the code to make it possible to view single files (maybe with DL'ing
      like @{"LHA" LINK LHA} or @{"ZIP" LINK ZIP}) from SHRINK-Archives. 

To get in Contact with me take a look to chapter @{"ADRESS" LINK BBSADVERT1}...
@endnode

@node EXE "SUPPORT OF EXECUTABLES"
@{b}                              EXE_PATH=<path>
-  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -
@{ub}
Here you specify the complete path to an @{b}EXEcutable Checker@{ub}, i.e. 
EXE_PATH=C:CHECKEXE. If this Tooltype is not set or the path is incorrect, 
EXE-Support is disabled.

If you set it correct, users have the ability to @{b}check AmigaDos-Executables@{ub}.
I use @{b}CheckExe by Shagratt/LSD@{ub}, but you could use every checker which supports
the normal DOS-Errorcodes (0,5,10,20). This is important coz if your favourite
checker doesn't return a valid errorcode (i.e. all went okay but Returncode=10)
you couldn't use it with mEGA-vIEW. I'm checking the ReturnCodes before 
continueing the program, so make sure that the Returncodes are DOS-compatible.
Also your ExeChecker should accept the following Syntax:

                          @{b}CHECKEXE <filename>@{ub}

and make sure that your checker supports redirecting of the output,otherwise
there could be problems. I have only the CheckExe-Checker, so I couldn't test
it with others...
If you plan to use ur own coded checker, make sure that you write your outputs
to Output(), otherwise the Redirection could make problems...!

If the selected File is packed,mEGA-vIEW shows you the used packer (if FileID-
Library recognize the packer of coz..). If you set the ToolType @{"EXE_FILEID" LINK EXEID}
correct, mEGA-vIEW searches for the @{b}Filedescription@{ub} inside the Executable after
displaying the Checkerresult and if found asks you to view the description.
If you don't specify the @{b}EXE_FILEID@{ub} ToolType correct, mEGA-vIEW return to the
fileprompt after showing the Informations from the ExeChecker.
@endnode

@node EXEID "SUPPORT OF FILE_ID.DIZ IN AMIGA-DOS EXECUTABLES"
@{b}                            EXE_FILEID=<path>
-  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -
@{ub}
Here you define the complete path to @{b}EXEDescript@{ub} written by @{b}Re/Y\o/MsT@{ub}, i.e.
EXE_FILEID=C:EXEDESCRIPT. If this Tooltype isn't set mEGA-vIEW wouldn't 
search for @{b}FILE_ID.DIZ@{ub} inside an Executable. If you set this ToolType correct,
mEGA-vIEW search for a Filedescription inside the executable after testing it.
If a description were found it will be displayed to the user. 
 
Big @{"Thanx" LINK GREETS} must go to @{b}Remo/MST@{ub} for his @{b}ExeDescript.@{ub}
@endnode

@node GUIDE "SUPPORT OF AMIGAGUIDE® - DATABASES"
@{b}                            GUIDE_PATH=<path>
-  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -
@{ub}
Here you specify the complete path to @{b}GuideToDoc@{ub} by fOX/rEMEDY^aSPECT, i.e.
GUIDE_PATH=C:GUIDE2DOCPROF. If this Tooltype is not set or the path is 
invalid, Guide-Databases were displayed with all special commands used by 
AmigaGuide®.

If you set it correct, users have the ability to view Guidedatabases like an
normal Textfile without the annoying '@{b}@@{ub}' , '@{b}{}@{ub}' and other commands only used
by AmigaGuide. To convert the desired Guide into an @{b}ANSI-File@{ub} you need the
CLI-Tool Guide2DocProf. You could use this Tool to convert any Guide-Database 
to an normal @{b}ASCII/ANSI@{ub} file. The Syntax for this Tool is :

                   @{b}GUIDE2DOCPROF <GUIDE>@{ub}

Were @{b}<GUIDE>@{ub} is the Guide you want to convert. This Tool writes the
converted Guide to STDOUT, so if you want to convert i.e. the mEGA-vIEW-Guide
to an ANSI-file, simply type this in your favourite shell:

        GUIDE2DOCPROF >RAM:VIEWER.DOCS CWORK:DOCS/mEGA-vIEW.GUIDE

This will convert the Guide '@{b}CWORK:DOCS/mEGA-vIEW.GUIDE@{ub}' into an ANSI-File
which will be created in '@{b}RAM:@{ub}' as '@{b}VIEWER.DOCS@{ub}' .

mEGA-vIEW calls Guide2docProf and redirect the output to a file temporary 
stored in ur @{b}Temp-Dir@{ub} (Could be set via @{"TEMP_PATH" LINK TEMP} ).

After displaying the converted ANSI-File will be deleted.

@{u}NOTE:@{uu} As some sysops noted, I have changed this command and replaced the
      old Program GuideToDoc by @{"ByteAndi/tRSi" LINK TRSIMEMBER} with the new one from fOX. The
      reason is that ByteAndi's tool crashes, if the selected Guide is too
      big...to avoid crashes fOX has written the same program in 100% ASM to
      give the maximum speed available...so don't wonder, just enjoy the fast
      speed of this Tool...

You could use (of course..:) your own converter, but make sure that your
converter returns the correct Errorcodes and supports the same call from
CLI like Guide2docprof, otherwise it won't work ! 
See Chapter @{"CHECKEXE" LINK EXE} for more Informations...
@endnode

@node ZOO "SUPPORT OF ZOO-ARCHIVES"
@{b}                             ZOO_PATH=<path>
-  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -
@{ub}
Here you specify the complete path to the ZOO-Packer, i.e. ZOO_PATH=C:ZOO.
If this Tooltype is not present or the path is invalid, Zoo-Archiv-Handling
is disabled. If this TT is set correct, users have the ability to @{b}view@{ub} the
contents of ZOO-archives or to @{b}Test@{ub} the integrity of the desired archive.

I've implemented this old packer only for one reason...I saw weeks ago a 
little Amiex-Arexx-Door, which includes this packer, and the Author writes
as Description, that this Door could handle more packers than mEGA-vIEW...:)
Well,I don't know what this Author think about mEGA-vIEW, but this fuckin'
aREXX-script was a 5 minute work, and mEGA-vIEW was developed over 2 Years of
hard work, and i don't want to see such shit...so I decided to implement this
old packer, too..
@endnode

@node ZOOM "SUPPORT OF ZOOM-ARCHIVES"
@{b}                            ZOOM_PATH=<path>
-  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -
@{ub}
Here you specify the complete path to the @{b}ZOOMCHK-Program@{ub} written by Carnivore
from BeerMacht, i.e. ZOOM_PATH=C:ZOOMCHK. Don't use here the original ZOOM-
packer, as this stupid packer don't support the testing of archives without
displaying any requesters !!! Always use only the ZOOMCHK program...

In fact that this packer isn't much popular, I decided only to support the
testing...if my registered Users want more informations, I will implement
the ZOOM-Sourcecode (available in good PD-Boards) into mEGA-vIEW, but that
was not neccessary yet..
@endnode

@node WARP "SUPPORT OF WARP-ARCHIVES"
@{b}                            WARP_PATH=<path>
-  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -
@{ub}
Here you define the path to WARPCK V1.4,i.e. WARP_PATH=C:WARPCK. Invalid
Pathnames to the checker disables this option...

WARP is a DMS-alike Packer, but has the difference that WARP could pack 
nearly anything, maybe with copyprotections...:) I'll want to support this
packer, 'coz i found many archives packed with warp, but don't know if they
are ok to download...so with this support everyone is able to check warp-
archives.
@endnode

@node LZX "SUPPORT OF THE NEW LZX-ARCHIVES"
@{b}                            LZX_PATH=<path>
-  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -
@{ub}
Here you specify the path to LZX V1.00, i.e. LZX_PATH=C:LZX. Invalid Path-
names disables the LZX-Support. If set correct, users could @{b}view@{ub} the contents
or @{b}test@{ub} the archive...

NOTE: This packer is the newest one available on Amiga...it combins very 
      good packrates with a lightning speed, but has a disadvantage in
      difference to LHA...it doesn't support yet the handling of recursive
      extracting of files from an archive...i.e. if you have a archive with
      the following files:

                           screens/node/SUXX
                           SUXX
                           BBS/AMIEX

..lha is able to extract the file SUXX without entering the whole pathname,
so if I want to extract it, i have to enter only SUXX, not SCREENS/NODE/SUXX,
and the FIRST file named SUXX will be extracted...but LZX currently doesn't
support this feature, here you MUST define everytime the whole path...and
therefor I have currently only the viewing/testing supported...for my
Registered users will come in the near future an update, which allows them
to simply extract files out of LZX-Archives, no matter if the files are
in different pathes inside the archive...but again: such features are only 
for @{b}REGISTERED USERS@{ub}, so if you want to use such features, please @{"REGISTER" LINK REGISTER}!
@endnode

@node TEMP "DEFINITION FOR A TEMPORARY WORKPATH USED BY mEGA-vIEW"
@{b}                             TEMP_PATH=<path>
-  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -
@{ub}
Here you could enter an alternate path for @{b}temporary files@{ub} which are used for
extracting and converting files. This Tooltype must not be set, coz the 
Default-Setting is '@{b}RAM:@{ub}'. If you have not enough free Memory you should set
it to a valid AmigaDOS-Path, i.e. "TEMP_PATH=DH0:T/" . All packers and other
Tools controlled by mEGA-vIEW uses the path you defined here for extracting,
converting or whatever. 

@{u}NOTE:@{uu} When you want to use the Ram-Disk as Temppath, always enter '@{b}RAM:@{ub}' as
      path coz the Ram-Disk is a dynamic Drive and therefor RAM: is always
      @{u}full (0 Bytes free!!)@{uu} . To let it work I have included two checkroutines.
      The first one checks normal ADOS-Devices like DF0:, HD0: etc. if there 
      is enough space on it. The second one will be activated only if you 
      enter @{b}RAM:@{ub} as path or disable this ToolType. In this case, mEGA-vIEW 
      will check your @{b}FREE MEMORY@{ub} instead of checking the free space on 
      the device. Other devices @{b}WOULDN'T BE@{ub} recognized, so @{b}T:@{ub} will be 
      checked as Device, not for FreeMem !!!!
@endnode

@node ACP "HOW TO FIND YOUR ACP-ICON TO LET IT WORK CORRECTLY"
@{b}                              ACP_PATH=<path>
-  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -
@{ub}
Here you specify the path to your @{b}ACP-Icon@{ub}. Normally, it's not necessary to
define this ToolType, but some Sysops told me that mEGA-vIEW didn't find ACP
coz they have no Searchpathes defined. If mEGA-vIEW couldn't find your ACP,
enter as <path> a valid AmigaDos-Path to your ACP.

@{u}NOTE:@{uu} In difference to the Packer-ToolTypes, you must define the @{b}PATH ONLY!@{ub}
      Don't enter here for example BBS:ACP, coz this results in BBS:ACP/ACP !
      If your ACP will be found in BBS:, enter ACP_PATH=BBS: . I'm using this
      ToolType coz I have no BBS online and therefor it won't be started via
      WBStartup. mEGA-vIEW won't found ACP without this ToolType, so I define
      this ToolType with my BBS-Directory (ACP_PATH=BBS:) and all works. 

This Tooltype is disabled by default (closed in Branches () ) and I recommend
first to try it without this ToolType. If mEGA-vIEW reports that ACP couldn't
found define it to the path were ACP could be found and all should work now.
@endnode

@node CALLERSLOG "ADDING COMMENTS TO CALLERSLOG"
@{b}                             CALLERSLOG=<YES|NO>
-  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -
@{ub}
Here you could choose if mEGA-vIEW should add a comment to the Callerslog when
a user tries to @{b}view/download a Restricted File@{ub}. By default, this Option is
disabled. To enable it, set the ToolType to @{b}YES@{ub}, i.e. CALLERSLOG=YES. For more
informations about @{b}Restricted Files@{ub} take a look to @{"RESTRICTED FILES" LINK RESTRICT}.

@{u}NOTE:@{uu} If you run a multinodeboard it could happen that Amiex @{b}crashes@{ub} while
      mEGA-vIEW adds the comment. @{u}This is not a bug from me !!@{uu} So don't think
      lame 'bout me when you see a guru while adding the comment. If this 
      happens, @{b}disable@{ub} this option (CALLERSLOG=NO) and you have no problems
      anymore.
      I don't know what AmieX does when two programs want to add a comment
      but this error should only happen on all AmieX-Versions @{b}<@{ub} 3.20 ... If
      you have a higher Version from AmieX (of coz ONLY REG. Versions !) and
      this error occurs, please @{"INFORM" LINK BBSADVERT1} me and i try to inform the Authors of
      AmieX to fix this problem.

@endnode

@node ONLYCHECK "HOW TO CHOOSE BETWEEN VIEWING & TESTING"
@{b}                           ONLY_CHECK=<accesslevel>
-  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -
@{ub}
Here you define which accesslevel is needed to @{b}View files/archives@{ub}. If you
don't specify this ToolType @{b}NO@{ub} user could view anything. If you set it correct,
i.e. ONLY_CHECK=50, all users with an accesslevel @{b}>=@{ub} 50 could view files with
the full support of all packers. All users with an accesslevel @{b}<@{ub} 50 could only
@{b}test archives@{ub}, @{b}viewing of textfiles is disabled@{ub}. Don't need to write more bout
this option, I think...
@endnode

@node DLLEVEL "ACCESSLEVEL TO DOWNLOAD FROM LHA/ZIP-ARCHIVES"
@{b}                           DL_LEVEL=<accesslevel>
-  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -
@{ub}
This ToolType defines at which accesslevel a user could Download @{b}*ONE*@{ub} File
from a @{b}LHA/ZIP-archive@{ub}. If this ToolType is not set or the user's accesslevel
is below the level defined here, the Downloadoption for @{b}LHA/ZIP@{ub} is disabled,
and the user could only view files. If the user has an accesslevel equal or
higher then the one defined here then he could choose if he want to @{b}view@{ub} or
@{b}download@{ub} a file from @{b}LHA/ZIP@{ub}. 

@{u}NOTE:@{uu} If a user has the Accesslevel for @{b}SYSOPVIEW@{ub} but not for Downloading,
      then the Downloading is disabled, too. @{"SYSOPVIEWLEVEL" LINK SYSOPVIEW} doesn't overwrite
      this to avoid Leeching from CoSysOps or other people who wants to abuse
      such a option.

When a user could Download, mEGA-vIEW checks two things before starting the
Download. First, mEGA-vIEW checks if the user has already enough Uploadbytes
to download the selected File. The check is simple but good: mEGA-vIEW take
the Bytes uploaded by the user and adds the Bytesize of the file he wants to 
DL. If the result is higher than the uploaded Bytes, mEGA-vIEW stops and 
inform the user that he has '@{b}Exceeded Bytes Limit@{ub}'. If the user has 
enough Uploadbytes to Download the selected File, mEGA-vIEW checks if the 
user's DailyBytesLimit will be high enough to download the file. If both 
checks are okay, mEGA-vIEW starts the ZModem-Transfer. 

If the User has a disabled Ratio, the checkings were skipped and he could 
Download a file no matter which Byte-Stats he has...

After transfering the File, mEGA-vIEW adds the filelength of the downloaded 
file to the users Dl-Stats and returns to the Fileprompt.
@endnode

@node SYSOPVIEW "DEFINITION FOR SYSOPVIEW"
@{b}                       SYSOPVIEWLEVEL=<accesslevel>
-  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -
@{ub}
Here you could define at which level users could view files @{b}outside@{ub} the BBS-
pathes, i.e. the user could enter '@{b}V DOCS:mEGA-vIEW.GUIDE@{ub}'. This ToolType 
overrides the @{"ONLY_CHECK" LINK ONLYCHECK} access. 

Of course all checkings for restricted Files will be made before displaying
the selected File to the user. If you don't specify it @{b}NO@{ub} users could view
anything outside the regular BBS-Pathes. I have defined this Tooltype to the
accesslevel of my Cosysops so they could view private files as long as they
were not marked as restricted.

To use the @{b}SYSOPVIEWCOMMAND@{ub} I've included an icon called '@{b}VS@{ub}' which let's you
use mEGA-vIEW similar to the @{u}original internal SYSOPVIEW-Command@{uu}. This Icon
is not neccassary to use the @{b}SYSOPVIEW@{ub}, but made things easier for you...:)

@endnode

@node RESTRICT "INFORMATIONS ABOUT RESTRICTED FILES"
                         @{b}RESTRICTED FILES@{ub}

AmieX has the ability to @{b}protect@{ub} Files against @{b}Downloading/Viewing@{ub} by adding
a FileComment (RESTRICTED) to those files. They are defined in the @{b}ACP-Icon@{ub}
with the ToolType @{b}RESTRICT.x=<file>@{ub}. When you start your BBS all Files defined
as Restricted in ACP were marked as Restricted in the FileComments. If you want
to protect other files not defined in ACP then add a FileComment to this file
with the DosCommand @{b}FileNote@{ub}. Take a look to your Dos-Manual for a detailed 
Commandsyntax.

Everytime a user tries to @{b}view/download@{ub} such files mEGA-vIEW informs the user
that this File is restricted and if you have @{"CALLERSLOG=YES" LINK CALLERSLOG} a Comment would be
added to your Callerslog with the complete Filename of the File the user tries
to view.

@endnode

